'''Sumy''' ({{lang-uk|<U+0421><U+0443><U+043C><U+0438>}} {{IPA-uk|<U+02C8>sum<U+026A>|}}, {{lang-ru|<U+0421><U+0443><U+043C><U+044B>}}) is a [[city]] on the [[Psel River]] in [[Ukraine]], and the [[Capital (political)|capital]] of the [[Sumy Oblast]]. As of 2004, the city's population is 283,700.  It is served by [[Sumy Airport]].

== History ==
[[File:Coin of Ukraine Sumy R.jpg|left|100px|thumb|Commemorative coin of Sumy's 350 year history]]
Sumy was founded in 1652 at the bank of the Psel River (a left tributary of the [[Dnieper]]) as a Cossack fortress. It was intended to protect [[Sloboda Ukraine]] from the [[Crimean Tatars|Crimean Tatar]] attacks. After their attacks discontinued and the territory was incorporated into the [[Russian Empire]], Sumy evolved into an important economical centre. During the [[Nazi Germany|German]] occupation of Ukraine during [[World War II]] (1941 &ndash; 1943), Sumy sustained heavy damage. The war over, destroyed parts of the city were rebuilt anew. Sumy has been a [[Twin towns and sister cities|twin town]] of [[Celle]], [[Germany]] since January 17, 1990.

The city used to be divided into two city raions (districts): Zarichny and Kovpak. However, they were liquidated in 2006.<ref>[http://w1.c1.rada.gov.ua/pls/z7502/A005?rdat1=08.12.2010&rf7571=42366 Verkhovna Rada website]</ref>

== Demographics ==
